10.body: SETTING THE AGENDA The delegates are expected to raise a motion to set the agenda. This motion requires a second. If there is no opposition to the motion,it is adopted by the chairboard.If there is opposition,the chairboard may accept 2-4 opposition speaches and move on with the voting procedure. OPENING SPEECHES Every delegate should deliver a opening speech after setting the agenda in the first official session. The opening speeches cannot exceed 1.30 minutes. GENERAL SPEAKERS LIST A general speakers list will be formed by the chairboard at the beginning of every offical session except for the first session. Delegates who are wishing to speak should raise their placards prior to the chairboards call. The gsl speeches cannot exceed 1 minutes. Delegates should come to the lectern after having the floor to give their speeches. Delegates wishing to remove their names from general speakers list should send a message paper stating their will to the chairboard. The chairboard preserves every right to close the general speakers list due to flow of the committee. MOTIONS Delegates should give their motions prior to chairboards call for the opening of the floor. After the floor is open points have the top priority in the order. Delegates should give their motion after gaining chairboards recognition by raising their placards. If there are more than one motions,the motion stated with a longer time range than the other motions will be voted first. A motion requires a second and no objections to pass.If there is an objection the chairboard will have a procedural voting. The chairboard preserves every right to grant motions without going for voting and limit the time for the motions. A motion sentence may be structured like this "Motion to talk about ___ in moderated/unmoderated caucus for ___ minutes.". CAUCUSES The time given for a caucus cannot exceed 20 minutes. Caucuses cannot be given a extention that is longer than the original caucus's duration Delegates cannot give extention to extention. Caucuses may be terminated prior to chairboards consent. First caucus of each session should be a moderated caucus There are two types of caucuses: MODERATED CAUCUS UNMODERATED CAUCUS

12.body: Refrain from using accessories that may promote any groups that are unrelated to their roles and are not said to be allowed in this document Refer to the conservative and formal side, when in doubt
12.title: All attendees must:

13.body: Should always wear three-piece(jacket, pants, dress shirt) suits. Accessories: Mandatory: Neck/Bow tie Allowed: Rings Belts Lapel/Tie pins (as long as it doesn't violate the first rule) Suspenders Cufflinks/Earrings/clips (as long as it doesn't violate the first rule) Pocket Squares Watches Refrain from: Bracelets Hats Gloves Necklaces Graphic ties Chains Shirts: Refrain from: Graphic shirts Flamboyant colors Allowed collars: Classic Semi-Spread Spread Button Down Wings Small Wings Unallowed Collars Eyelet Mandarin Bands Standing Jacket & Pants: Always wear matching suits Italian style is recommended Prefer darker colors Refrain from informal patterns Always use formal shoes
13.title: Male attendees:

14.body: Should wear Pants/skirts/dresses The minimum skirt length is two fingers lower than knee length Should refrain from informal patterns flamboyant colors Shirts: Refrain from: Graphic Shirts Flamboyant colors Revealing styles Maximum reveal can be three fingers under the neckline Always use formal shoes Are encouraged to wear Jackets There are no required accessories for female delegates however it is allowed to wear these: Jewelry (as long as it doesn't violate the first rule) Foulard (refrain from flamboyant colors and informal patterns) Hair accessories (crowns are only permitted for the delegates and chair board in the crisis committees) Watches Pins(as long as it doesn't violate the first rule)

5.body: Meetings of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization will be held at a time and place designated by the sponsoring institutions. Official language is English for the committee
5.breadcrumbs: Rules of Procedure » PART I. MEETINGS
5.title: PART I. MEETINGS

6.body: The preliminary agenda for regular meetings of the Council and Committees shall be drawn up by the sponsoring institutions and communicated to the members prior to the opening of the first official session and the agenda is supporting the African Union
6.breadcrumbs: Rules of Procedure » PART II. AGENDA
6.title: PART II. AGENDA

7.body: Each NATO country and partner country shall be represented by one delegate.
7.breadcrumbs: Rules of Procedure » PART III. REPRESENTATION
7.title: PART III. REPRESENTATION

8.body: The Committee will have a Chairperson from the Secretariat who will have full powers to ensure proper functioning of the committee. The Chairperson may preside over all meetings, or may designate its co-chair to do so. The Chairboard shall have the responsibility of ensuring the smooth operation of the Committee through interpretation and enforcement of the Rules. In addition to exercising powers described elsewhere in the Rules, the Chairperson shall declare the opening and closing of each meeting, direct discussions, accord the right to speak and announce decisions.He/she shall rule on points of order and, subject to these Rules, shall have complete control of the proceedings at any meeting. The decision of the Chair may be appealed by any delegate. This motion is debatable by one delegate in favor and one against, after which the motion shall be put to a vote. The Chairperson’s decision will stand unless overruled by a two-thirds majority of members present and voting. Rapporteur The rapporteur of the committee shall: Make notes of everything spoken within the context of the meeting, Receive and distribute the documents of the committee, In the absence of the Vice Chair, take his place, if needed. Academic Asisstant The academic asisstant may help the delegates by: Giving them information Suggesting resolutions if it does not interferes the debate.
8.breadcrumbs: Rules of Procedure » PART IV: THE CHAIRBOARD
8.title: PART IV: THE CHAIRBOARD

9.body: Quorum The chairboard may permit the debate to proceed when at least one third of the delegates participating in the work of the assembly present. This number of present members shall be required for any decision to be taken. Speeches No one may address the without having previously obtained the permission by the chairboard. The chairboard shall be in charge of drawing up a list of speakers.
